# The adjacency matrix representation:
# Use INF for nodes that don't have a direct edge connecting them.
graph = [
    [0, 5, INF, 10],
    [INF, 0, 3, INF],
    [INF, INF, 0, 1],
    [INF, INF, INF, 0]
]

# Run the algorithm
floyd_warshall(graph)

'''
Theory: The "All-Pairs" Champion

So far, you might have heard of Dijkstra's algorithm. Dijkstra is great, but it's a Single-Source algorithm (it finds the shortest path from one specific city to all others).

The Floyd-Warshall algorithm is an All-Pairs shortest path algorithm. It calculates the shortest possible distance between every single pair of vertices in a given graph. Like the Longest Common Subsequence we did earlier, Floyd-Warshall uses Dynamic Programming.
2. The Approach (The "Intermediate" Vertex)

The core logic of Floyd-Warshall is brilliantly simple. It asks one question repeatedly:
"Can I get from vertex i to vertex j faster if I take a detour through an intermediate vertex k?"

    We start with a 2D distance matrix. If there is a direct edge between i and j, we put its weight in the matrix. If there is no direct edge, we put Infinity (∞). The diagonal is 0 (distance from a node to itself).

    We pick a vertex k to act as our "detour" or "intermediate" city.

    We look at every possible pair of source (i) and destination (j) cities.

    We check the math: Is the distance of (i→k)+(k→j) strictly less than the currently known distance of (i→j)?

    If yes, we update our matrix with the new, shorter distance.

    We repeat this process, making every single vertex in the graph act as vertex k one by one.

Complexity Analysis

    Time Complexity: O(V3) where V is the number of vertices. Look at the code: there are three nested for loops, each running V times. While O(V3) sounds slow, the constants are very small and the loop is incredibly tight, making it the best choice for dense graphs (graphs with lots of edges).

    Space Complexity: O(V2). We need a 2D matrix of size V×V to store the distances between all pairs.
'''